## Core Concepts and Theory

### 1. Class and Object

A class is a user-defined data type that contains data members and member functions. An object is an instance of a class. In this lab, different classes such as `ATM`, `Circle`, `LibraryBook`, `Physics`, `Maths`, and `Temperature` were used to understand class-based programming.

---

### 2. Private Data Members

Private data members cannot be accessed directly outside the class. They help in protecting data from unauthorized access. In this lab, values such as balance, radius, book details, marks, and temperature were kept private.

---

### 3. Static Data Members

Static data members are shared by all objects of a class. They do not belong to a single object but belong to the class as a whole.

For example, in the `ATM` class, `totalTransactions` and `totalMoneyMoved` were declared as static members to store combined transaction details of all ATM objects.

---

### 4. Static Member Function

A static member function can access only static data members of a class. It can be called using the class name without creating an object.

In this lab, the function `showStats()` was used to display the total number of transactions and total money moved across all ATM objects.

---

### 5. Const Member Function

A const member function does not modify the data members of an object. It is mainly used for functions that only read or display values.

For example, functions like `getArea()`, `getCircumference()`, `display()`, `toFahrenheit()`, and `toKelvin()` were made const because they only return or display data.

---

### 6. Const Object

A const object cannot call non-const member functions because non-const functions may modify the object. It can only call const member functions.

In the `Circle` class, a normal object was allowed to call both const and non-const functions, but a const object was only allowed to call const functions.

---

### 7. Friend Function

A friend function is not a member of a class, but it can access the private and protected members of that class. It is useful when a function needs access to private data of two or more classes.

In this lab, friend functions were used to calculate total marks and compare temperature values.

---

### 8. Const Reference

A const reference allows an object to be passed to a function without copying it and without allowing the function to modify it. This makes the program efficient and safe.

In the `LibraryBook` task, `printBookInfo(const LibraryBook& book)` was used to print book details safely.

